narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: differentiation for multivariable functions, inverse function theorem, implicit function theorem, thorough introduction to manifolds, differential forms, and how integration of differential forms connects with Stokes Theorem.

This course was a big step up in abstractness from anything Ive done before, but Professor Neitzke did good job of walking us through the material. When I look back at how much we covered, I realize that the course completely changed the way I think about math. It was incredibly rewarding.

- Lots of practice with mathematical proofs
- Manifolds
- Vector Analysis
- Multivariable Calculus in R^n

I know better about multi-variable calculus in a deeper sense. Manifold introduces to a more powerful setting to talk about integration and some differentiation. I think the most important takeaway from this course is the intuition for change of variable. Once you have the right intuition, which the professor is excellent in conveying, you can essentially build up the whole theory yourself.
I learned very detailed foundamentals of algebra and analysis on basic concept of manifold.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Very quick coverage of material, but all-in-all a great professor with a ton of knowledge about the content. I would not have changed anything about the course.

I think the course itself was excellent. Maybe we could have spent a little more time on Stokes Theorem. I do wish we had gotten more practice with the kinds of problems that were going to be tested. We would study all this theory, but then be tested mostly on applications.

Strengths: Extremely passionate, knowledgeable, and dedicated professor. Is relatively lenient with homework extensions, and gives a solid (not too much, not too little) amount of homework.

Weaknesses: Homework grading turnaround time is a little iffy - I often had to wait 3 weeks to get the grades for my psets back.
Some parts of the notes can be more rigorous, minor errors sometimes can be dreadful.
It is very interesting and intensive in algebra. Hence, sometimes students might be at loss due to the math.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Gives a thorough introduction to vector analysis and manifolds
I absolutely would. I think anyone interested in anything the la course touches on would love it.

Yes, absolutely. Other than being required for the math major, I think every student who wants to should take this course simply because of how well-taught it is. Prof. Neitzke really cares about all of his students.
I would definitely recommend this course to other students, especially people who are not comfortable with multivariable calculus and want to do something about it.
Yes. If manifold is usually used, I would say this course is useful.
